General Emergency Response

-Emergency alert system;
-Periodic emergency training for employees;
-Communication systems with local emergency responders and regulatory agencies;
-Emergency drills/training with terminal personnel, regulatory agencies, and community emergency responders to enhance response skills and coordination among agencies;
-Mutual Aid with Local Fire Departments; and
-Participation with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC) or equivalent.

Further, the Bay City Terminal complies with the National Fire Protection Association's (NFPA's) Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) Code (NFPA-58) requirements for LP Gas storage. In addition to the presence of appropriate controls to prevent possible releases of butane, if a release does occur, a Smart Plan/Emergency Response Action Plan (ERAP) is in place for the Facility with response activities being coordinated with the Bangor Township Fire Department and Bay County LEPC.

C. FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

The Bay City Terminal has an excellent record of accident prevention. The terminal maintains records for all significant accidental chemical releases inclusive of root-cause analyses and associated follow-up actions, where appropriate. There have been no accidents within the past five (5) years resulting in consequences covered under the EPA RMP reporting requirements.  The Terminal tracks all process incidents per API 754 guidance.

D. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM

